<div type="commentary"><!-- The plates were no longer available when Kielhorn edited them from Sir Walter Elliot's estampages and brief notes, provided to him by Fleet. No image of the seal is available; the seal legend is reported by Kielhorn from Elliot's notes as "Tribhuvanāṁkuśa", and I assume that śrī was present before the name as usual. Kielhorn is, moreover, expressly unsure whether the notes really belong to this set of impressions. According to these notes, the plates were received from Mr. Porter, Collector of Masulipatam, hence Kielhorn calls them "Masulipatam (?) Plates", but given the lack of accurate provenance and the uncertainty even of the available information, I prefer to name them after an internal locality.
-->
<!--In stanza 3 (sragdharā), we have a glide sandhi fusion between lines a and b, the first time I've ever seen this happen. Stanza 5 (mandākrāntā) has a more regular fused caesura in line c. Stanza 10 (sragdharā) also has a fused caesura at the second point in line b. -->
</div>



